Sarah,

Thank you for the detailed comments. I have taken instructions from my client and can respond as follows.

On the liability cap: my client is prepared to move from three months to four months of fees as their final position. They are not able to accept six months given the overall contract value and the risk profile of the services being delivered. This is a firm position and escalating it further will not change the outcome.

On intellectual property: my client accepts that bespoke deliverables developed exclusively using your data and specifications should vest in your client upon full payment. They require a perpetual, royalty-free licence back to use those deliverables for internal benchmarking purposes only. The data usage restrictions you propose in Section 14.3 are acceptable with one amendment: the thirty-day deletion obligation upon termination should be extended to sixty days to allow for orderly system decommissioning.

On payment terms: my client agrees to thirty days net. On the late payment rate: my client will accept one and a half percent per month as a compromise.

On the CPI cap: my client accepts a cap of four percent per annum rather than three. This reflects their own cost base exposure and is the minimum they can accept.

On governing law: my client agrees to non-exclusive jurisdiction. They do not agree to a mandatory mediation step given previous experience with mediation causing delay in time-sensitive disputes. They propose instead a mandatory senior executive escalation period of fifteen business days before either party may issue proceedings.

The remaining points you raise regarding Schedule A, Section 3.4, termination fees, and data return are being reviewed and we will revert by close of business tomorrow.

We are available Wednesday afternoon for a call.

James Whitfield
Partner, Commercial Disputes
